title: The Pocket Socket High Tech Pocket Protector

description.text:
This is a pocket protector. It will stand guard in your pocket and prevent anything from damaging your pocket by first asking the offending device not to spill any ink or anything while residing in your pocket. If the offendee still persists the Pocket Socket will wield a flame thrower and torch the loser. So get yourself some Kevlar reinforced office attire and go through your day knowing your pockets are secure and free of any ink.

This was designed for a co-worker to hold 2 small paint markers with a diameter of .225" and one large paint marker with a diameter of .575". Also a standard pencil (.390" pocket), an ink pen (.445" diameter pocket), There is also a pocket for a Mead Memo pad and a slot for a 6" scale. The goal was to keep the items held into the pocket protector even when it is turned upside down. So I modeled in some spring tabs into each pocket that holds the items securely. It works rather well for a first attempt.

Enjoy.

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.200 mm

Infill:

Notes:

This printed amazingly well considering it is the largest part I have printed to date. Even more amazing was the fact that it actually worked as intended. We flipped it upside down and everything stayed put. The pockets for the markers and pencils were maybe a tad snug, but they will wear in just fine. The guy I made it for actually liked it the way it was.

Use supports from build plate only as this was designed to print without any internal support. All overhangs have an angle that should print flawlessly except the bottom of the clip on the front of this part. If you need any other print settings post a comment and I will reply asap. Will be happy to share the printer profile if anyone needs it.

title: Dell Wyse Thin Client Z90DW 2.5 hard drive caddy

description.text:
I bought a Wyse Z90DW thin client on eBay for the cost of a Raspberry Pi. I am going to use it as an inexpensive NAS (network attached storage device). To do that I needed a caddy to hold hard drives as the case has no provisions for them. I will probably buy more and run a distributed file system like GlusterFS or Ceph but FreeNAS would also be an excellent choice.

With these specs it is much more robust than a Raspberry Pi:

  • AMD G-T56N
  • AMD Radeon HD 6310
  • 2GB (max 8GB)
  • mPCIe, 2 x SATAIII, Ethernet, USB3

I designed the caddy to be easy to install, hold one or two hard drives, and not require a bunch of case modding. The rounded feet slide into place easily and the whole thing is held in place by case compression. The number of 2.5'' hard drives you can fit is largely determined by their thickness and how svelt of a right angle SATA adapter you can get. I did have to clip off a retaining hook on the main case panel but its right next to a screw point.

I got a lot of information here: parkytowers.me.uk

This probably works with most of the Z90 series but take a look inside and see.
Trial and error and a digital caliper.

title: Warhammer Quest (1995) Goblin Proxies
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I'm working on a complete set of printed proxies to cover the entire range of possible rolls on all 10 levels of the monster tables from the WHQ Roleplay Book.

I only ever owned the base set, and I always wanted to collect them all but could never afford it when they were still on the market.

I've leaned heavily on dutchmogul's amazing collection of gaming miniatures. Some of these figures are only resized versions of his, some are modded versions of his, and a rare few are scratch modeled by me.

I've gone through the list and pared it down as much as possible. My goal is to handle any given roll, but not worry about trying to cover any two rolls... I chose not to distinguish between a Savage Ork and a Black Ork, for example, and I only considered An Ork to differ from and Ork champion if they could both appear on the same roll. So you basically end up with Orks, Bigger Orks, and a Boss Ork. Finally, if you have 2D6 goblins that you roll for bows or spears, I choose to take that as 1D6 w/bow and 1D6 with spears to keep the numbers down.

This is the Goblins, up to ~battle level 4. More to come, and more races to follow.

This is a Raspberry Pi or USB Hub Modeled after DS1 with a few inspirations for the trenches from similar models. I personally use this as a Raspberry Pi Zero powered Console server at work. The entire model has been built from scratch using Fusion 360, and the files are included if anyone wishes to edit/remix.

Print all the parts as oriented, with supports for the 90 degree overhangs on a few parts. For the USB hubs, I used a few generic 4 port wired hubs from Amazon, and cut away the shells. The grooves on the trench plates should have the metal edges slide in nicely. Secure the 2 trench plates together by snapping them together, or with 3mm screws/bolts if you use the old bolt trench patterns. Place a USB cable in the groove on the Power Plug pieces, and then screw it into the bottom.

For a bit of extra flare, I used a woodburning kit to poke a hole in the dish, and insert a green LED using the "Light Tube" and "Light Tube Cap". You must glue the light tube to line up with the hole you make. Looks really nice if plugged into the 5V on the Pi! The pictures are from an earlier version, the Dish on the released version is solid and one piece with the top half of the globe.

Additional Note: The "Scale 75%" files are for if you want to print a smaller version. You have to scale all the other parts down 75% in your slicer software, but these pieces will fit perfectly without any scaling into the rest of a 75% scaled model.

因為剛開始想做的是小黑炭那種圓球形的東西，所以我的黏土是一個大圓形，後來把球的一端拉出來，就變成蝌蚪的尾巴了。我覺得頭大的生物都很可愛，所以把蝌蚪的頭也做得很大。顏色是我很滿意的菱角色，本來只是拿一塊一塊不同顏色的黏土揉在一起，再多加一點紅色，本來黯淡的黑色就變成了跟菱角一模一樣的顏色，而且蝌蚪的尾巴我做成彎曲的形狀，所以他真的很像菱角......但黏土硬掉之後尾巴的尖端就斷掉了。
你對於作品感到滿意嗎？哪裡還有進步的空間呢？
對於最後的黏土成品我很滿意，雖然完全不是一開始想像的樣子，但這樣邊做邊改我覺得更有彈性，更能把自己的想法完整呈現出來。不過如果以後還有機會做類似的作品，我會想做大一點，因為作品太小很難把細節強調出來。眼睛的部份我也想再修改，右眼做得很完整，可是左眼不小心把黑眼珠用到眼白的地方了，所以我又貼了一小塊白色黏土上去，可是還是有點痕跡，這是我覺得有點可惜的地方。

請描述從黏土到建模時，你在設計上的修正（可能是小部份或是置換大主題）             建模比我想像中的困難很多，不像用手捏黏土一樣可以隨意改變形狀，所以我的建模成品其實跟我的黏土作品有一段差距，最明顯的就是頭跟尾巴的連接處從延伸變成接合了，沒有那麼流線型的感覺。但建模也讓蝌蚪的眼睛變得比手工做出來的形狀更圓。因為眼睛和嘴巴要準確嵌合在蝌蚪的頭上，所以角度我也有調整過。 tinkerCAD軟體的哪一項功能最吸引你？讓你感到驚艷？             一開始看老師操作的時候覺得很簡單，結果自己用的時候超不順，對操作不熟悉，對空間也沒什麼概念，光是把眼白成功地嵌到頭上就做了二十分鐘，然後眼白眼珠左右不對稱，我再重新修改每個部位的相對位置和大小，真的是一個很漫長而且崩潰的過程。 在你的設計作品中，描述一個最複雜的結構，並試圖描述它是由哪些向量幾合構成的？             我的作品沒有使用很多幾何圖形，最複雜的應該就是臉的部份了，我用的是一個正圓形，再調整左右的寬度讓他變成橢圓形，麻煩的就是把眼睛嘴巴黏上去，只要從不同角度看，就會發現其實不在五官應該在的位置，然後就必須重新調整每一個部分。 3D列印的生活應用層面，試圖以醫療、建築、和教育三大面向給予描述。             建築：利用3D列印，建築師和建築公司做出比加工件輕60%且堅固的比例模型，讓客戶可以從空間各個可能的角度檢視產品來得到一個清晰的印象。透過3D印表機可將原本僅存在數位世界中的資料實體化，數位化的製造過程更可將人為的誤差降到最低，免除過去建築模入的人為意識或變更產生與實體不符之狀況。    醫療：3D列印已經被應用到生產移植器官和器械等醫療領域。    教育：3D列印讓學生可以不再使用昂貴的用傳統減量方法製作的模型，而是利用3D技術直接設計和列印模型。學生在課堂上學習3D應用的相關知識，開發3D列印的應用潛力，在這個過程中同時學習工程，設計，和建築的相關知識。化石，歷史文物的複製也可以通過3D列印完成，避免了對珍貴文物可能造成的損傷。對製圖設計有興趣的學生還可以將複雜的部件組裝成完整的模型。3D列印為地形圖的繪製提供了新視角。學生物的學生通過3D模型可以更好的學習觀察人體內部器官和其他生物標本。學化學的學生則可以觀察分子的3D模型，分析化合物間的關係。 給大家一個印下來的理由吧（投票）                        其實我沒有很希望他被列印下來，因為建模的成品跟我理想中的樣子還是有點差距，我覺得黏土做出來的作品還是最好看。

黏土創作設計概念 1.請試圖描述作品的形狀、比例、顏色
作品很理所當然的是一朵花。有黃色的花瓣共6朵，頭是白色的橢圓形，眼睛是兩個黑色細長的橢圓，嘴巴是由一個長條加一個半圓曲線組成。花的莖是綠色的，莖的底部有一個半圓綠色底座。頭高51.0，寬52.8。莖高49.0，寬37.32。底座高12.0，寬20.0。
2.你對於作品感到滿意嗎？哪裡還有進步的空間呢？
大致上挺滿意的，只是花瓣使頭看起來不像橢圓形。有時間的話可以修這一塊部分。還有我覺得大手其實滿有喜感的，但是也是沒有時間做了。因為手也有弧度要修很久。

1.請描述從黏土到建模時，你在設計上的修正（可能是小部份或是置換大主題） 我把花的兩隻大手拔除了，改成莖的底部有底座。2. tinkerCAD軟體的哪一項功能最吸引你？讓你感到驚艷？ 立體的作圖讓我感到很新鮮，但是操作上要注意不然物件都會被拉到奇怪的地方。不過一旦作品完成後，看著自己的作品就會很有成就感！3. 在你的設計作品中，描述一個最複雜的結構，並試圖描述它是由哪些向量幾合構成的？ 花瓣的弧度很難抓。我是先用半圓形拉長，再找出有弧度的形狀（社群造型生產器的循環梯形和Clip）放在半圓底部的兩邊，並把有弧度的形狀設成孔，接著再把他們設成群組。 4.3D列印的生活應用層面，試圖以醫療、建築、和教育三大面向給予描述。 醫療：牙套、假牙、義肢。 建築：房子的結構、模型。 教育：讓小孩對於立體空間更有概念。5. 給大家一個印下來的理由吧（投票） 3D列印很難得成本又很貴，不印白不印！

痾....大便狀，我是用圓環堆疊出來的，最上面的部分是用圓錐把他用的尖尖的。顏色其實也沒有特別調出來就是點上面原本就有的咖啡色(這咖啡色我覺得還蠻適合的)然後眼珠就是白色，眼球黑色。

開始做黏土的時候，我像做出既美觀又可以支撐手機的架子，但很快的我在美觀這方面遇到了阻礙，一開始，我嘗試做出類似彎彎的Q版人偶，後來沒有美術細胞的我很快就放棄了，人偶總是做成四不像，再來我嘗試用兩個水滴形狀的黏土做出一隻黑貓，然後我又失敗了，最後我放棄美觀這個條件，我做出了一個“好用”的手機架也就是『我的寵物』。 作品的前端是長方形為基礎，一端呈弧形與下面的地盤連接最後有小塊凸出能夠架手機，另一端則是到下方有弧形與地盤連接。長寬高是5：6：7，黑色。前方有眼睛和嘴巴。
美觀方面是不太滿意，但就實用性來說，是可行的，如果外觀方面再多一點修正能更好。

在3D建模設計上，我更換了顏色，也讓整體形狀變得更整齊。其中，建模裡的切割功能很吸引我，切割必須靠著想像力，方向和角度對了，就可以做出各種想要的形狀，非常好玩。 我的作品中，身體得彎曲弧度是最難最複雜，也是令我最苦惱的地方，他使用兩個肥皂和形狀的方塊當基底，再用圓形屋頂去切出弧度，最難的地方就是讓身體的弧度與尾巴的弧度取得平衡，因為是要放手機的，底座就不能切得太薄，雖然看起來很簡單，卻是用很多很多的方塊去調整而來，幸好有老師幫忙，最後做出來很有成就感。  3D列印的技術真的很廣泛，比起以前你必須找到適合的材質，特殊的工具才能做出東西，現在3D建模方便很多也簡單很多，醫療夠利用特殊的材料，印出仿真的器官，這樣就不需要依賴器官捐贈。建築方面能夠減少材料在切割上的浪費，也更能達到客製化的需求。而教育方面不只能讓老師做出特殊的教材方便教學，更能讓學生發揮創造力做出屬於自己的東西，提升自信心。  既有紀念價值，在生活上也可以實際應用，雖然造型上可能不對你的口味，但她擁有的價值絕對超過擺在一旁的裝飾品。

title: Pop-up GPS mount for mavic clone

description.text:
I was having trouble with interference of the magnetometer in the 3dr gps because of it's proximity to the video Tx and battery and I was also unhappy with the fit of the original parts so I came up with a pop-up gps mount which gets the gps/magnetometer a little further away from the interfering components.

There are hooks underneath the cover to attach small rubber bands to make the gps spring up and stay up but in practice I have found that just the friction in the pivot points is enough to hold it in place.

I used 1/16" or 1.6mm wire for the bottom pivot pins and servo screws for the rest.

I printed in carbon fibre ABS, https://blueprinted.co/products/abs-carbon-filament?variant=20667791878 which may have helped with shielding the emf but not significantly. It is great stuff to print with though as it almost eliminates shrinkage.

My compass calibration is much better now and the quad loiters in a locked position.

title: Tool to level X-axis of Prusa i3 (8mm rods)

description.text:
This Thing is a modified version of mangtronix X/Z leveling tool.

I imported the model into blender, cleaned up most of the triangulated faces, then re-cut both the "claw" and the "L" to be suitable for 8mm smooth rods. The new cuts have a 4.2 mm radius (so 8.4mm diameter), and a fairly high poly count for extra-smooth curves.

I beveled the edges of the "claw" to account for the usual flaring that happens on bottom surfaces, so that such flaring can't affect the claw's effective diameter. I also beveled the upward-facing edges of the "L" to account for potential, minor edge artifacts that could distort that end of the part.

I recently bought a new alternator for my 2001 Mercedes Benz ML320 only to find it has a different plug connector for field excitation as the one currently on my vehicle. Mine has an old style screw down connector for the exciter coil, while the new one has a 2 pin plug. I checked on a Mercedes Benz G300CDI and it just used one wire with this exact style plug.

So I just made a new plug to adapt my old style connector to the new plug. I did find an alternator that had the old style connector, but it was $400 more expensive.

This quick adapter saved me $400 for a 1 hour print.

I've uploaded this because it may help somebody out. Volkswagen, Audi and BMW and other brands who use Bosch alternators also use the same new plug, and I've adapted the design to fit both kinds of new connectors I've found as pictured. Exciter coil/Warning lamp 'should' be the rounded end of the connector. The G300CDI I checked the connection was shunted to both spade connectors of this exact new kind of plug. I connected it to mine with just one wire on one spade connection.but I take no responsibility if your vehicle varies from this. Use at your own risk.

description.text:
I designed this because, like many other model railway enthusiasts, I found myself stuck with many already laid and working points that I wanted to power, but could not get underneath them to drill a hole, or position a motor correctly

I have chosen to use servos and an arduino for my point control, so to overcome this I designed this adaptor that easily fits over the lttle "stick up" bar on the end of a Peco point tie rod and also allows connection of 1mm piano wire securely into the outer end. As can be seen , it is pretty unconspicuous once in place, and if painted black of maybe grey, looks like a genuie piece of railway equipment.

This means you can locate the point motor almost anywhere else you want ( on top ofr under your baseboard) and use piano wire, usually inside a piece of 1.5mm inside diameter flexible tubing.that will guide it securely.

The first line consists of locations of classic encounters, such as the gothic stone dungeon, the dank caverns, and the half timbered town, all of which is easily compatible among the majority of fantasy settings. The second line is inspired by iconic computer based dungeon crawling role playing games where legendary settings are yours to design. The third line is driven by a high fantasy setting with tales of epic proportions. Several more themes and expansions for each line are planned to be released afterwards.

A little info about the 3 lines

“Classic Encounters” includes all your generic, classic settings. Basic dungeon, taverns, caves, city streets.

“Vintage Vault” is about recreating those classic video games and even board games. Everything in the game is recreated here in tile form. Relive the adventures of old or create new ones.

“Lost Realms” are deluxe sets. They're created just like a D&D module. There is an adventure theme already set out for a DM to build upon. So, these sets are heavily themed for instant adventuring.

comments.text: La estela de Barros es una estela cántabra discoidea gigante del siglo III a. C. encontrada en Barros (localidad del municipio de Los Corrales de Buelna, Cantabria), declarada bien de interés cultural en 1985. El nombre actual, muy popularizado, lo comparte con el de La rueda de Santa Catalina, dado por H. Breuil, y el de Rueda de la Virgen, nombre popular hoy en desuso; además existe una segunda estela de Barros, reconstruida a partir de los fragmentos encontrados en el muro de una iglesia. Se cree que señalaba la tumba de un guerrero de finales de la Edad del Bronce o principios de la Edad del Hierro antes de haber sido movida de su emplazamiento original. Mide 1,66 m de diámetro por 0,40 de espesor, y está situada sobre una base de 1 metro de altura y 0,80 de ancho, unas medidas impresionantes en este tipo de símbolos. Aunque es la estela discoidea más famosa de Cantabria, no es la mayor; el contradintel de la ermita de la Virgen de la Rueda es parte de otra gran estela, de diámetro 1,90 m. Se conservan otros ejemplares de estelas gigantes tanto prerromanas como romanas y medievales, algunas de ellas en la misma localidad.
